# API Route Conventions

## Route Handler Structure

Use Next.js App Router Route Handlers with named exports:

```typescript
import { NextRequest, NextResponse } from "next/server";
import { supabaseAdmin } from "@/lib/supabase";
import { logger } from "@/lib/logger";

const log = logger.child({ service: "api-tasks" });

export async function GET(request: NextRequest) {
  // ... handler logic
  return NextResponse.json({ data }, { status: 200 });
}

export async function POST(request: NextRequest) {
  const body = await request.json();
  // ... handler logic
  return NextResponse.json({ success: true }, { status: 201 });
}
```

## Webhook Endpoints

- Path: `/api/webhooks/[provider]/route.ts`
- Authenticate via `x-webhook-secret` or `Authorization: Bearer` header against `WEBHOOK_SECRET`
- Validate payload, then enqueue via BullMQ — return 200 immediately (don't block on processing)
- Each provider has an adapter in `lib/providers/` that normalizes the transcript format

## Error Responses

Return consistent JSON error shapes:

```typescript
if (!task) {
  return NextResponse.json({ error: "Task not found" }, { status: 404 });
}

try {
  // ...
} catch (err) {
  log.error({ err }, "Operation failed");
  return NextResponse.json({ error: "Internal server error" }, { status: 500 });
}
```

## Dynamic Route Params

In App Router, params come from the function signature:

```typescript
export async function POST(
  request: NextRequest,
  { params }: { params: Promise<{ taskId: string }> }
) {
  const { taskId } = await params;
  // ...
}
```
